Singapore Stocks: Golden Agri-Resources, Olam, STX Pan Ocean

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-04-12T09:42:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-11/olam-singtel-tiger-air-yangzijiang-singapore-stocks-preview.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
declined 0.7 percent to 3,138 at the close. More than twice as
many stocks fell as rose in the benchmark index of 30 companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 14.3 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Palm-oil producers: Crude palm-oil futures for June
delivery dropped in  Kuala Lumpur  today, its first loss in three
days.  Golden Agri-Resources Ltd. (GGR)  , the world’s second-
biggest palm-oil producer, decreased 2.8 percent to 70.5
Singapore cents.  Indofood Agri Resources Ltd. (IFAR)  , the
palm-oil unit of  Indonesia ’s biggest noodle maker, slipped 2.2
percent to S$2.25.  Wilmar International Ltd. (WIL)  , the
world’s biggest palm-oil trader, lost 1.3 percent to S$5.23.  Olam International Ltd. (OLAM)  , a supplier of
agricultural commodities, climbed 2.8 percent to S$2.95. The
company said Tata Chemicals Ltd. (TTCH IN) will invest $290
million in Olam’s urea manufacturing project in Gabon. The
Indian company will hold a 25.1 percent stake in project, while
Olam’s stake will be reduced to 62.9 percent and the Republic of
Gabon’s interest will be cut to 12 percent, Olam said.  STX Pan Ocean Co. (STX SP),  South Korea ’s No. 1 bulk
carrier, dropped 0.7 percent to S$11.20. Citigroup Inc. cut its
rating on the stock to “hold” from “buy.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in  Singapore  at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 